<DOC><DOCNO> AP880323-0154 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1540EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Ministers     03-23 0205</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Iraq-Ministers,0212</SECOND><HEAD>Light andamp; Heavy Industry Ministers Replaced by Army Officer</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Saddam Hussein has dismissed theministers of light industry and heavy industry from his Cabinet andreplaced them with the army officer who supervises the manufactureof Iraq's military hardware.   A presidential decree issued Tuesday night and publishedWednesday by government newspapers said Heavy Industry MinisterAbdul-Tawab Mulahuwaish and Light Industry Minister HatemAbdul-Rashid were relieved of their duties.   It did not say what prompted their dismissal, but added thatCol. Hussein Kamil has been appointed Minister of Industry andMinerals.   Government sources said the cabinet reshuffle is designed tomerge the two ministries and give the military industry a boost.   Kamil, a career military man, has been heading the War IndustryCommittee that supervises the manufacture of military equipment.   Iraq says it is making some of its own ammunition and weapons,including long-range missiles.   More than 100 missiles have been fired at the Iranian capital,Tehran, since Feb. 29 in a missile duel by the nations.   While the Iraqis say these were homemade, Western militaryanalysts believe they are Soviet-built, surface-to-surface Scud-Bsthat the Iraqis have equipped with boosters to increase their range.</TEXT></DOC>